003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert de Cantilupe was born in 1071, in Canteleu, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France, his father, Walter de Cantilupe or Cantilou, was 21 and his mother, Euphamia Cantilupe, was 16. He had at least 1 son with Fern Wright. He died in 1130, in Clécy, Calvados, France, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1071–1130":"1071–1130","1082–1163":"1082–1163","1107–1161":"1107–1161","1050–1100":"1050–1100","1055–1138":"1055–1138","1107":"1107","1138":"1138","1100":"1100","1055":"1055","1130":"1130","1163":"1163","1161":"1161","1050":"1050","1071":"1071","1082":"1082","Clécy, Calvados, France":"Clécy, Calvados, Prantsusmaa","Canteleu, Normandy, France":"Canteleu, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"